truffle will automatically figure out whether to call or send your function based on the contract ABI which is generated during Solidity compilation. So you can just write:
javascript
await contractFactory.createDog('doggy'); // send fn
await dog.getName();  // call fn
and they should both work as expected. 
Additionally, the return value of createDog in JS will be a transaction receipt, not an address. To retrieve the address you should .call your public storage mapping dogs with the appropriate key and then instantiate the created address using Dog.at. 
