. This actually will also fail when the very first element of the arrays match. The code goes like this:
    function notEqual(int[] arrA, int[] arrB, string message) public returns (bool) {
        var r = arrA.length == arrB.length;
        if (r) {
            for (uint i = 0; i < arrA.length; i++) {
                if (arrA[i] == arrB[i]) {
                    r = true;
                    break;
                }
            }
        }
        _report(!r, message);
    }
```
So if a = [1,2] and b = [1,4] - it will consider them equal and throw an assert when checking notEqual. . PR#769 contains the fix for this as well. . Closing this in favor of https://github.com/trufflesuite/truffle-core/issues/101.

